<!--
Part B – Relative Position 
5.Create a box and apply position: relative.
6.Move the box 40px to the right and 20px down. 
7.Explain how the box's original space is affected. 
8.Create two adjacent boxes and move one using relative positioning. 
Describe the behavior of the other box.
-->
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Relative Position</title>

    <style>
        body {
            font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
        }

        .box {
            height: 60px;
            width: 60px;
            background-color: yellowgreen;
            text-align: center;
            line-height: 60px;
            position: relative;
            left: 40px;
            top: 20px;
        }

        .container {
            margin-top: 50px;
        }

        .box1,
        .box2 {
            height: 60px;
            width: 60px;
            display: inline-block;
            text-align: center;
            line-height: 60px;
        }

        .box1 {
            background-color: aqua;
            position: relative;
            left: 40px;
            top: 20px;
        }

        .box2 {
            background-color: aquamarine;
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>

    <h2>Relative Position Example</h2>

    <div class="box">1</div>

    <h2>Two Adjacent Boxes</h2>

    <div class="container">
        <div class="box1">2</div>
        <div class="box2">3</div>
    </div>

    <h2>Explanation</h2>

    <p>
        The first box uses <code>position: relative</code>.
        Applying <code>left: 40px</code> moves the box 40 pixels to the right,
        and <code>top: 20px</code> moves it 20 pixels down from its original position.
    </p>

    <p>
        The original space of the box is still reserved in the document layout.
        Other elements behave as if the box is still in its original location.
    </p>

    <p>
        In the second example, only Box 2 is moved using relative positioning.
        Box 3 remains in its original position and does not move to fill the empty space left by Box 2.
    </p>

</body>
</html>
